"1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1313":"1313","1235":"1235","1453":"1453","1287":"1287","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Radbourne, Derbyshire, Inglaterra":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Brailsford, Derbyshire, England":"Brailsford Green, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":18,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":43,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":56,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":65,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":110,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Braylesford was born in 1272, in Brailsford Green, Derbyshire, England, her father, Henry de Brailsford III, was 66 and her mother, Isabel Picot, was 42. She married John de Chandos in Radbourne, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Radbourne, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1272–":"1272–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1253–1287":"1253–1287","1259–1304":"1259–1304","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1260–1313":"1260–1313","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1206–1258":"1206–1258","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1272":"1272","1382":"1382","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Abt 1285":"umbes